<section xml:id="sec_fifth-trig" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>The Fourier Cosine and Sine Series</title>
  <introduction>
  <p>
    A function <m>f(x)</m> is said to be an even function if <m>f(x)=f(-x).</m> 
    e.g., <m>\cos x {,} \sec x {,} x^{2} {,} x \sin nx {,} </m> etc. are even functions. 
    The graph of such a function is symmetrical with respect to <m>f(x)</m> axis. 
    The area under such a curve from <m>-\pi</m>  to <m>\pi</m> is double the 
    area from 0 to <m>\pi</m>.
    <me>
     \therefore  \int\limits_{-\pi}^{\pi}f(x)\,dx = 2\int\limits_{0}^{\pi}f(x)\,dx 
    </me>
    here,
    <me>
    a_{0}= \frac{1}{\pi}\int\limits_{-\pi}^{\pi}f(x)\,dx = 2\int\limits_{0}^{\pi}f(x)\,dx;
    </me>
    <me>
      a_{n}= \frac{1}{\pi}\int\limits_{-\pi}^{\pi}f(x) \cos nx\,dx = \frac{2}{\pi}\int\limits_{0}^{\pi}f(x)\cos nx\,dx;
    </me>
    and 
    <me>
      b_{n}= \frac{1}{\pi}\int\limits_{-\pi}^{\pi}f(x) \sin nx\,dx = 0  \quad \text{[Half-Range Series]}
    </me>
    </p>

<figure>
      <sidebyside widths="35% 35%">
          <figure xml:id="fig-fig52a">
              <caption>Even Function</caption>
              <image source="fig52a.png"/>
          </figure>
          <figure xml:id="fig-fig52b">
              <caption>Odd Function</caption>
              <image source="fig52b.png"/>
          </figure>
        </sidebyside>
  </figure>

    <p>
      In this case, Fourier Series is represented by 
      <me>
        f(x) =\frac{a_{0}}{2}+\sum\limits_{n=1}^{\infty}a_{n} \cos nx
      </me>
      and is called Fourier cosine series as <m>b_{n}=0</m> for all the even 
      function [figure <xref ref="fig-fig52a"/>]. 
      Again, a function <m>f(x)</m> is said to be an odd function if <m>f(-x) = -f(x)</m>. For example,
      <m>x {,} \tan x {,}x^{3}{,} \sin x{,}</m> etc. are odd functions. The graph of such a function is 
      skew symmetrical with respect to <m>f(x)</m> axis. The area under such a curve from 
      <m>-\pi</m> to <m>\pi</m> is zero. That is, 
      <me>
        \int\limits_{-\pi}^{\pi}f(x) \,dx =0; 
      </me>
      here 
      <me>
        a_{0}= \frac{1}{\pi}\int\limits_{-\pi}^{\pi}f(x)\,dx = 0; 
      </me>
        <me>
          a_{n}= \frac{1}{\pi}\int\limits_{-\pi}^{\pi}f(x) \cos nx\,dx = 0;
        </me>
        and 
        <me>
          b_{n}= \frac{1}{\pi}\int\limits_{-\pi}^{\pi}f(x) \sin nx\,dx = \frac{2}{\pi}\int\limits_{0}^{\pi}f(x) \sin nx\,dx \quad \text{[Half-Range Series]}
        </me>
            In this case, Fourier series is represented by  
            <me>
              f(x) = \sum\limits_{n=1}^{\infty}b_{n} \sin nx
            </me>
             is called Fourier sine series as <m>a_{0}</m> and <m>a_{n}</m> are zero in 
             all the odd function [figure <xref ref="fig-fig52b"/>].
      </p>
     </introduction>
 
 <subsection xml:id="subsec-fourier_sum">
  <title>Summing of Fourier Series</title>
  <introduction>  
  <p>
     Since the Fouries series is a convergent series, it converges to 
  </p>
     <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>f(x)</m>, if <m>x</m> is a point of continuity.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\frac{f(x+0) + f(x-0)}{2}</m>, if <m>x</m> is a point of discontinuity. 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
         <m>\frac{f(-\pi+0) + f(\pi-0)}{2}</m> at <m>x=\pm \pi</m>, if <m>x</m> is a point of discontinuity.
        </p>
      </li>
     </ol>
  </introduction>

  <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-half_range">
  <title>Half - Range Series</title>
  <p>
    If a half - range series for a function  <m>f(x)</m> is desired, then the function 
    is generally defined in an open interval <m>[0.\pi]</m>, which is half of the 
    interval <m>[-\pi, \pi]</m> and hence the name half - range. In this case the 
    function <m>f(x)</m> is expressed as an odd or even function. For interval (0,c) 
    <me>
      a_{0}= \frac{2}{c}\int\limits_{0}^{c}f(x)\,dx;
    </me>
    <me>
      a_{n}= \frac{2}{c}\int\limits_{0}^{c} f(x) \cos (\frac{n\pi x}{c}) \,dx; 
    </me>
    <me>
      b_{n}= \frac{2}{c}\int\limits_{0}^{c} f(x) \sin (\frac{n\pi x}{c}) \,dx
    </me> 
    </p>
</subsubsection>
 </subsection>


  </section>

